<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-5">
  <title>Resources for 10/5</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the graph of a function <m>f</m>, sketch the graph of <m>f^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Solve application problems where functions are created by adding, subtracting, multiplying, and dividing other functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-graph-inverse">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Graphing Inverse Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>graphing inverse functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="auoBd-Rkqxo" />

    <example>
      <title>Graphing Inverse Functions</title>
      <p>
        Graph the inverses of the following functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>First graph</p>
            <image width="50%">
          	  <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="inverse-graph-prep-1">
	              <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
        			    <definition>f(x)= 2*sqrt(2)^x-4</definition>
    		          <coordinates bbox="(-4,-4,4,4)">
        		  		  <axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
			              <graph function="f" />
          			  </coordinates>
        	      </diagram>
            	</prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Second graph</p>
            <image width="50%">
        	    <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="inverse-graph-prep-2">
		            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              		<definition>f(x)= -2*sqrt(-x-4)+2</definition>
			            <definition>g(x)= 2*sqrt(x+4)+2</definition>
              		<coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
			              <axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" hticks="(-10,1,10)" vticks="(-10,1,10)" />
            				<graph function="f" domain="(-10,-4)"/>
        		      	<graph function="g" domain="(-4,10)"/>
            			</coordinates>
            		</diagram>
        	    </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y=x^2</m> (Try)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-combining-applications">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applications of Combining Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>combining functions in applications</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="mQKiX9OGViY" />

    <example>
      <title>Combining Functions (Applications)</title>
      <p>
        Create the following functions and solve the application problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Jojo is selling fancy chairs.  If the price is <m>p</m> dollars, Jojo can sell <m>d(p) = 900-3p</m> units.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If Jojo sells their chairs for <m>p = $3</m>, what is the total revenue that Jojo takes in?  Do the same for <m>p=$10</m> and <m>p = $20</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use the same reasoning as in (a) to find a formula for Jojo's total revenue when the price is <m>p</m>.  We will call the total revenue <m>R(p)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What are the domain and range of <m>R(p)</m>?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You are building a rectangular fenced-in space for your dog right next to your home with 100 feet of fencing.  One of the sides of the area is the side of your home.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>x</m> is the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home, and if <m>y</m> is the length of the side not attached to your home, what is the area of the fenced-in space?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home is <m>x</m>, what is the area <m>A(x)</m> of the fenced-in space?  Hint:  Let <m>y</m> be the length of the side not attached to your home, and solve for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If the length of the side of the fence not touching your home is <m>y</m>, what is the area <m>a(y)</m> of the fenced in space?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What are the domain and range of the above functions?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

